Recieved a call from EC Office in Fredericton, NB about a voicemail report of wind damage near Elphinstone, MB on June 1, 2005. Proceeded to do a follow-up call to get details: Caller said that sometime on June 1 between 5 pm local and 3 am on the 2nd strong winds caused damage to an adjacent property. Unsure if damage was caused by a tornado or not. Pictures of the damage forthcoming. His location is on Thompson Lake which is 10 km NE of Elphinstone, MB. Only damage to his property was a leaky basement from 6 inches of rain over a 5-hour period. However, 1/2 mile N of his property a 400-yard wide swath of trees was knocked down in a straight line. Trees were poplar and had trunks approx. 12 inches in diameter. Adjacent to the trees, a property had its shingles torn off, patio furniture tossed about (one chair thrown 300 yards N), damaged to a BBQ and winds moved a dog house a considerable distance. Pea-sized hail at 5 pm reported but not enough to cause damage. However, neither his trees nor his mother's trees 100 yards E of his yard were damaged. He never saw a funnel cloud touchdown. He only witnessed the damage to the property to the north of his the next morning (June 2).

THIS IS A FOLLOW-UP DAMAGE REPORT FOR THE PILOT MOUND TORNADO ON THE EVENING OF JULY 2, 2005. The tornado first touched down at approx. 8:20 pm CDT about 8 miles due N of Pilot Mound (WPO). It continued on a southeasterly trek and retracted from the ground approx. 5 miles NE of WPO, forming a double vorticity during this time (25 minute duration). Judged through a damage survey two days later to be a strong F2 tornado. The damage survey conducted by members of the PASPC-Winnipeg on Monday, July 4 turned up the following: a poorly-anchored mobile home was destroyed, a steel-reinforced machine shed (40'x80'x30') that had been bolted into a cement foundation was also destroyed, trees 12 to 18 inches in diameter were snapped 10 to 20 feet off the ground, several sheds/barns flattened (debris left laying beside foundation), empty grain bins tossed 100's of yards away (that were bolted into the ground), insulation left hanging in the trees, mud splattered on the sides of homes, at least 10 power poles knocked over, a school bus was pushed 30 feet backward over a crabapple tree,several deceased poultry, a 1"x8" piece of wood was embedded half-in and half-out of a house and the safety glass on the same house was shattered but not broken by flying debris. Most of the tops of the trees were no where to be found, presumably strewn miles away from the trunks still in the ground. The width of the damage path was twice measured to be 1.3 km. Several pictures of the damage taken by staff members. Hail the size of tennis balls also fell following the tornado causing some additional damage to property not already destroyed by the tornado.

Reading just /Summary of damage in the Markerville area on Aug 10: Damage was obs to start around the Raven area ~50km WSW of Red Deer and continued NE of Red Deer to the Forestburg area. Main damage seems to have been caused by the combination of loonie to Golf ball size hail and winds in excess of 100km/h.In the town of Markerville and surrounding area is where most damage was caused. Farmers are reporting that the crops are so damaged that they can not even salvage the remaining stumps for silage. In the town of Springbrook, which is co-locate with YQF, nearly every building was damaged. Siding either has holes in it or it was completly removed. YQF reported 20mm hail and winds gusting up to 65kts. Pictures show that there accumulations of >5cm.Also within the town of Springbrook is the Air Cadet summer training camp. Talking with Warrent Office Jason Bacon he said that nearly all windows on the west side of the barracks were smashed out and that 3 cadets were injured as a result of the storm (2 from flying glass and one from falling down a wet stair case that has windows facing west). Red Deer advocate reporting that on Hwy 2A between Red Deer and Springbrook that cars were getting stuck in hail accumulations of 21cm. Jamie Smith who was driving home at the time said that her car was "Bottoming out" on the hail along hwy 54 west of Red Deer. Steve Ramsey from Parkland Fertelizer in Penhold said that they had the door of their Quonset ripped off (one found nearly 100ft from the starting point) and a empty hopper was blown over. Numerous reports of large trees being blown over in the area west of Red Deer but all seemed to be pointing in the same general direction (east). Red Deer itself received very heavy rain and approx 2cm accumulation of hail. The main damage within the city appears to have been the heavy rain with streets still flooded on the afternoon of August 11. The Prentiss AWOS (NE of Red Deer) reported 45.1mm in one hour at 23Z. On Hwy 36 half way between Alliance and Galahad there was a report of dime size hail that lasted for approx 20min at 0150Z. No reports were received to the E of Hwy 36. The EPWS was triggered for this storm just after recieving the weathe obs from YQF and the report from Phillip Anderson that there was golfball sized hail.

Quote from CTV TV Calgary website: "Rain, hail, snow, strong winds and lightning hit the city of Calgary Thursday afternoon leaving a path of destruction in its wake. Emergency crews responded to a bizarre roof collapse in the citys northeast. Witnesses say they heard a huge "whooshing" noise and then the sound of flying debris slamming and banging around. The gust of wind was so strong it moved a massive heating unit on the roof of a business called Alberta Fire and Flood Restoration, ripping a hole in its roof. The office below was exposed and ceiling tiles got sucked up through that hole. The wind blew open doors on the building. It also smashed out the windows of several cars in the parking lot. Some people are speculating this was a small tornado, but that is not confirmed. Another area hit hard was Inglewood where the storm ripped the tops off trees and sent them crashing into fences. There are also smashed windows and damaged homes in the area." ***Time estimated from radar. Duration: 0.50 Hours. Wind estimated over 100 km/h.

Registered watcher called in to report extremely heavy hailfall 20 mi NE of Stettler, with most stones toonie-sized to golfball-sized. The ground was completely covered with hail - "looks like snow all over the ground" - and it was a "total whiteout" in terms of visibility. Hail had been falling for 10 minutes and was still coming down at the time of the call. There was comparatively little rain, but she did notice some gusty winds. She couldn't go outside to assess damage yet. Update: Hail was still falling steadily at 21:44Z, with size still ranging from loonie to toonie. The wind was gusting at about 50 kph from the SSW, and the water accumulating from the melted hail was past the caller's ankles. Hail was piled up against her front door to a depth of about 2.5 inches. The temperature dropped to 7 degrees during the hailstorm. Update: Steady hailfall persisted until approximately 22:15 PM, with stones loonie-sized or larger. Update: Final rainfall measured at 3.1 inches, and 3 inches of hail piled on the ground

Radar indicates that damage may be due to outflow winds, however funnel sighting and damage photos more indicative of tornado.

Multiple reports from town indicate strong winds (app. 100 km/h) causing damage: broken trees, roof areal, grain bins, buffalo was killed from debris, said very low clouds with fingers, patio furniture, fences, swings, gazebo lifted and thrown against car causing vehicle damage, twoonie size hail, building he was in at the time was lifted about a foot and a half and saw boards that were thrown sticking out of the building walls. Most indicated the wind lasted from 20 seconds to 4 minutes and could hear the loud whistling. The Spruce Home school had a satellite tower knocked over and roof damage. Town office had not heard any reports

RCMP called to report funnel cloud @ 18:32. Pea sized hail was also falling. Call was secondary from RCMP, called person at site. Person said, "Funnel cloud did not touch down. Location 1 mile S of Grosse Ile. The funnel cloud as seen was approx 1.5 miles west of Warren. It did touch down about a half mile from where first funnel was seen. As I was standing there, another short funnel cloud formed off to the north, about 300 yards away from me. It travelled southeast, then went back into the cloud. Approximately 15 minutes later just southeast of Gross Isle, a larger funnel shaped cloud formed behind the storm front, but is stayed just below the cloud and did not go lower. It was very large, perhaps a half mile/mile across, about 2 miles from where I was on 6 highway. At this point, a second storm came with large rain drops and pea/marble sized hail. During all of this, there was significant cloud rotation with wind being directed NE/NW toward the rotations, while the storm front carried on SE.

Callback to RCMP found wind damage continuing along the path of the storm - trees uprooted, siding and roof tiles torn off, etc. Duration: 0.27 Hours

It is possible that the damage was the result of a tornado as funnel clouds were reported from this storm system and an RCMP officer reported a tornado to the E of the Mills Farm. Storm caused a lot of wind damage to property near Bladworth. Many trees down, the barn was moved off the foundation. It was an old barn, not sure how it was secured. Graineries were moved all around the yard and thrown about. All of them were empty. Also got some hail, bigger than marbles, not sure of actual size. Damaged some of the crops due to the wind driving it down. She said it looked kind of like a sheet of hail coming down. When asked if they saw a funnel or anything to indicate if a tornado hit, she said that they couldn't see anything with the rain, but the damage was fairly localized. It didn't exactly carve a path, as their entire yard was hit. Event Lasted about 20 minutes.  Wind gust estimated at 120 km/h.

Called resident based on media interview of damage. Event started at 4pm in North Grove on shore of Buffalo Pound Lake. Reported that the winds shifted intensely in the 30 minutes prior to the event, from SE, to SW to W. Hail: There was mostly peas and marble sized hail, but some stones were as big as golf balls. Damaged the roof and vehicles. The side of the house is pitted with hail marks. The wind was so strong that it was driving the hail and rain parallel to the ground, into the house. Wind: Unsure of how fast the wind was going, easily over 100 km/hr. The wind was the worst in the last 5-6 minutes of the storm. Blowing hard enough that the window was bending in, at first they thought that the window was going to break from the tension. Steal Patio furniture on the deck was piled up at the corner about 12 ft high. Shingles from the room were peeled off. Trees all over the property were damaged and some even uprooted, including a 60ft tall, 50 year old tree. 2 doors down from their property, a neighbour also had damage.

Streets, underpasses and some buildings flooded. Report of water inside St Vital Mall in the food court, Chapter's and Silver City movie theatre. Flickering lights and some power outages reported. Hydro poles on fire from lightning strikes. Some trees hit by lightning. Damage to festival tents at the St Norbert Market and Filipino Street Festival. Some branches snapped by the wind. Hail flattened plants/gardens, severely damaged crops, smashed windshields, dented vehicles, damaged roofs, dented/punched house siding, took down small branches and shredded leaves off of trees. Kelvin Heppner on twitter reported that his corn crops were ripped by the hail. Hail was still on the ground 4 hours after the storm according to Dineen Marie on facebook. 25.7 mm of rain was also reported at the Altona Mb Ag station. The rain was enough to cause some street flooding. Numerous photos saved. Max wind gust of 60 km/h also recorded at the Mb Ag station.

Reference Location: Howe Point Road, Souris -- 225, Howe Point Road, Eglington, Kings County
Notes:
A CBC news report was used to gather this information and it is based off report of hail damage and an initial estimate of crop loss by farmer Peter Townshend. He claims that hail from a severe thunderstorm defoliated over 90% of one of his 100 acre field on Howe Point Road in Souris, PE. He also claimed this will result in the loss of possibly greater than 1,000,000 lbs of potatoes this season. All start times are estimated from historical radar images. 

***A severe thunderstorm watch was issued for PEI at 1424z, July 21st.
***A severe thunderstorm warning for Kings County, PEI was issued at 2327z, July 21st.

Hail size is based on social media reports sent to CBC radio. Unable to locate reports, but heard it on air on CBC radio on the morning of the 22nd.

Student on the desk talked to two residents at Fawcett Lake - Curtis (587-877-0746) and Clint. Curtis is the manager at the Fawcett Lake residence, he can find numbers of other people on the residence that experienced the storm. They are located at Fawcett Lake East resort. 5 or 6 residents supposedly saw a funnel cloud, no pictures were received of said funnel cloud. Damage reports included multiple fallen trees - mostly uprooted though some were snapped. The snapped trees were healthy poplars and some spruce trees. Curtis noted that the damage appeared to follow a definite path. Other damage reports included sheds destroyed, trailer roofs ripped off, tin roofs carried about a kilometer, trailers moved or tipped, and a shed lofted and carried about 150 feet. One family was inside one of the trailers that was tipped and a child was injured - very minor though, no hospital visit needed. Only pea sized hail was reported with the storm. Trees fell in different directions apparently, and much damage to sheds and trailers came from trees falling on top of them. Some RV trailers were reported to have lifted and moved slightly. As of now, it is being recorded as POSSIBLE tornado, but not confirmed. Meteorological circumstances were not indicative of a tornado at the time, however a landspout could be possible. For more information, refer to Kyle Fougere - kyle.fougere@canada.ca. Pictures of damage are saved.  UNCONFIRMED.

Reference Location: Beaver Lake Area/NW of Wolf Lake
Notes: At approximately 5:45 local time, a call came to the office from an RCMP officer in the Lac La Biche area who reported that he was seeing a tornado on the ground along the highway east of Lac La Biche and that he was heading towards it. The call was short and not much information was received as the officer was driving with his sirens on and said he could not talk much. There was a significant couplet on radar and tornado warnings were issued before this call was received. The couplets lasted for several scans on radar. Approximately 15 minutes after the RCMP phone call, a video was posted on Facebook from Amanda Quinney of a definite, large rotating funnel that appeared to touch the ground multiple times. The video caption said that she was near Beaver Lake. An attempt has been made to contact Amanda to try and receive more information. Later, the same RCMP officer - Srgt Clarke - called back and reported that there was toonie sized hail that damaged police vehicles and covered the Lac La Biche area. He also clarified that he did not actually see the funnel touch down, but that there was a definite funnel - tree coverage is likely to blame for him not seeing contact. At the moment, no reports of damage have been received, and more information is being sought for. Amanda Quinney called the office to report more information at about 3:30 local time on June 29th. She said she was at Beaver Lake on the Powow grounds and from the field at the grounds she could see it perfectly. She was looking south-southeast. The tornado touched down at about 4:25pm and lasted about 2 minutes (roughly the duration of her video), she could see clear funnel to ground contact. About a minute after she stopped recording it touched down again and was clearly visible on the ground for about another minute. Another funnel much closer to the Powow grounds was reported to come extremely close to touching down as well and had clear rotation but did not touch down. No damage was reported by Amanda, she couldn't see damage and hadn't heard of any. She is going to send more pictures via email to the student and the storm account.

Multiple videos and pictures were received via social media of a clear tornado/waterspout over Cold Lake. The first picture came in at about 2:26 UTC and was not very clear, but shortly after multiple clear photos were received of a definite waterspout on Cold Lake. The pictures and videos were saved. We reached out to the observer who took the first video and he clarified some details - they were on the north/northwest side of the lake (North Bay), looking southeast roughly towards the city of Cold Lake. The tornado lasted about 5-10 minutes. Hail was associated in the area as well - about quarter sized hail. As soon as the tornado made landfall, it dissipated quite quickly, though it did appear to be on the beach/land for a little bit very very briefly. The resident who saw it very clearly from his cabin was James Hilborn (780-974-3863). No damage reports have been received and it is unlikely that there was damage. Tornado confirmed.

Images of significant damage to tree, trailers and structures have come in.  Countless trees down, trailers flipped or severely damaged, and reports of outhouse structures and small buildings being lifted from their foundation and tossed a short distance.  Images show countless trees down in the region. 3 minor injuries have been reported with this storm. One hiker who was reported missing has since been found. Storm damage survey crew rated the tornado as a high EF1 due to the uprooted trees not having very deep roots. Quite extensive storm damage in Eston, SK. One house has its roof torn off and walls collapsed. Building looks old and not the best structure though. Some other houses with roof damage/part of the rood torn off. Silo in a ditch a kilometre out of town. A garage blew into power poles. Community centre had roof damage as well. Hail damage to buildings from hitting at high velocities. Some trailers flipped and one destroyed. Power out for 24 hours in the town. Trees down. Localized street flooding and golf ball sized hail with damage to siding of houses. One house with a sharp piece of a 2x4 piece of wood stuck in the side. Start time is radar estimated 1:40Z. Pictures saved in Severe Weather Photos. Wind damage of this extent may have been near 150 km/h. No tornado has been confirmed.

Called into the town of Nordegg and received a report of nickel to quarter sized hail that had just barely finished at the time of the call. Just before the call ended however, hail began falling again, though smaller than before.

A picture on twitter shows a hailstone in Brancepeth around the size of a quarter. There were also many reports of damage in Brancepeth from strong winds. A news report from CKOM reported toppled train cars and farm equipment. The report also mentioned many snapped and uprooted trees. A person who was investigating the storm from the nearby R.M. of Birch Hills office said they found many power poles snapped and 4-6 destroyed transmission line towers. This caused a widespread power outage in and around Prince Albert. They also talked to a family in the area and the family reported the roof of their pole barn and part of their house roof was blown away from the wind. The person did not hear of any funnel cloud reports from the locals. Although the storm looked to have a strong consistent rotation, the person said the locals were convinced it was a plough wind as all the damage looked to be in a straight line directed towards the north. Will be logged as a severe wind event along with the severe hail due to the nature of the damage.

Possible tornado reported west of Estevan, photos in severe weather folder. Many photos show funnel clouds appearing west of Estevan with some appearing to touch down. One video of someone near Rafferty Dam clearly shows a well-defined funnel with ground circulation over what looks to be McDonald Lake. The environment looked to support non-supercell tornadoes, however the storm looked to have supercellular features in some pictures. The forecasters leaned towards calling it a supercell tornado since the best shear was in this area and it may have been just enough to support a supercell. People on twitter reported one funnel cloud that lasted until about 23:05Z that did not touch down. Afterwards, there was another funnel after the first one lifted that did touch down (this tornado). Based on the reports and radar, it is estimated that the tornado touched down at ~23:10. Toonie-sized hail was also reported near Estevan at 23:18Z. This is will only count as one severe thunderstorm event in the chronologies as the hail was not reported at least 15 minutes after the tornado.

At approximately 6:30Z, a funnel cloud was spotted above the lake in Sambaa K'e. This funnel cloud was associated with the severe thunderstorm that occurred in the area, which also produced hail and strong winds. The storm caused branches of trees to be broken, and two boats were blown from the lake to a nearby pond located 200 ft away. No damage to the boats occurred. Spruce, poplar and shrubs were reported to be ripped from the ground due to the storm at camps located on the southwest and northeast side of the lake. Based on the damage reported, the wind speeds may have ranged from 85-120 km/h. There was a cell service outage and power outage that occurred at 7:20Z-7:40Z.

Structural and tree damage was reported in Cypress County west of Medicine Hat after a storm passed through the area. Paramedics responded to the scene though Alberta Health Services reported no injuries. Several farm animals perished. An NTP ground and drone survey was completed on July 18-19, 2022. Damage assessed as EF2 tornado, with an estimated max. wind speed of 190 km/h, track length of 7.80 km and max. path width of 300 m. Tornado motion was from the SW (approx. 230 degrees). Satellite imagery review revealed notable hail damage along the storm track. A downburst developed as the tornado was dissipating and caused EF1 damage in Redcliff.

Call-out to Hat Furnace & Duct Cleaning reported nickel size hail and localized flooding. Multiple power lines snapped. Fortis reports over 7000 homes without power. Reports of an RV tipped over on highway. Multiple trees snapped.Iris reported a maximum gust of 93km/h at the Medicine Hat Airport, storm chaser reported gusts of 136km/h with handheld anemometer https://twitter.com/NZPChasers/status/1549114005414748161. Home in Echo Dale had roof blown off, golf cart tipped, and small structures blown around yard. Report claims this was due to a tornado https://www.instagram.com/reel/CgKnnorAyPd/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link. Cypress county released a Tornado AEA Alert claiming a tornado has touched down in the area of Highway 523 and Highway 1 at approximately 1:50 p.m. There has been no visual reports confirming a tornado or funnel clouds. Structural and tree damage was reported in Redcliff after a storm passed through the area. No injuries have been reported at this time. An NTP ground and drone survey was completed on July 18, 2022. Damage assessed as EF1 downburst, with an estimated max. wind speed of 150 km/h, with weak damage in multiple locations over an area at least 6.0 km long and 6.0 km wide. Satellite imagery review revealed notable hail damage along the storm track. An EF2 tornado that developed in Cypress County west of Medicine Hat dissipated southwest of Redcliff.
